

// ── Intro ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Generalizing swing to subdivision systems other than binary ones naturally
requires becoming familiar with odd subdivisions, such as triplets or
quintuplets. In this session, I propose that we focus specifically on
quintuplets.

// ── Section 1 ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

= Vocabulary of Patterns

When working with four subdivisions per beat (sixteenth notes over a
quarter-note pulse), we are used to thinking of rhythms as being built from a
small vocabulary of elementary patterns. In practice, any rhythmic line can be
described as a sequence of just six basic rhythmic "words" (or seven, if we
include the simple quarter note):

#figure(
  image("Figures/voc4.png"),
)

Note that we deliberately exclude patterns that start with a rest. Unlike
silences occurring within the subdivision grid, a silence on the beat is almost
always perceived as a "loud silence": it functions perceptually as an onset,
not as an absence of sound.

We establish a similar vocabulary for the quintuplet subdivision:

#figure(
  image("Figures/voc5.png"),
)

The idea is to practice each of these patterns (suggestion: keep the first two
for the end of the practice session) by using them as templates to articulate
musical phrases, improvise lines, or construct grooves. Within each pattern,
one can also explore variations of articulation, accentuation, and phrasing.


= Cross Rhythms

After spending some time with each pattern we can then combine them to perform
simple cross-rhythms within the quintuplet subdivision:

#figure(
  image("Figures/cross5.png"),
)

The main difficulty lies in not confusing the cross-rhythm cycle with the beat
itself. The risk of a banana-skin effect is high: without a strong internal
pulse, the cross-rhythm can easily take over and be mistaken for the beat.
Maintaining a solid pulse feel is therefore essential in order to audiate the
cross-rhythm as a shifting structure, preserve its displacement function, and
keep the underlying beat stable.

// ── Section 3 ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

= Swinging the Quintuplet

For this reason, applying some swing to the quintuplet subdivision proves
extremely useful. As we have seen, when swing is applied to a subdivision
system, it reinforces the feel of the beat (the groove effect). Moreover, it
has a complementary effect: it strengthens the perception of the subdivision
system itself by giving it a recognizable and consistent structure.

To become familiar with quintuplet subdivision — and especially when studying
cross-rhythms — it is therefore recommended to apply a chosen swing to the
quintuplets right from the start. For this purpose, we will use a
first-order#footnote[The order of a pattern made of LONG and short values is
defined as the absolute difference between the number of LONGs and the number
of shorts. For example, the patterns [2,1,2,1,2] and [2,1,1,2,1] are both of
order 1, since the counts of LONGs and shorts differ by one. By contrast,
[2,2,2,1,\ ] is of order 2. In general, quplets of lower order carry less
potential energy, which corresponds to higher entropy, and therefore tend to
feel more balanced and stable.] Quplet with maximal entropy, namely $Q(5,7)$
or $Q(5,8)$. Since a non-zero groove balance further reinforces the sensation
of the pulse, my preference is for a rotation of $Q(5,7)$:

#figure(
  image("Figures/Q(5,7).png"),
)

= Tuplet ≠ Subdivision

We make a distinction between subdivisions and tuplets. Subdivisions divide the
beat and are therefore contained within the beat cycle. Tuplets, by contrast,
are considered as such — and distinguished from subdivisions — only when they
span a duration that is not a beat cycle, as is the case in a cross-rhythm.

Just as a pattern can be obtained by progressively swinging a subdivision
system, a tuplet can be obtained by progressively evening out a cross-rhythm
pattern. We can use that approach to access some difficult tuplet ratios such
as 25:7:

